The Magistrate's Seal

The toll collector at the rail depot spreads a map across his makeshift desk, a plank balanced on two stone cairns, and traces a route with one ink-stained finger. He's explaining the new administrative boundaries to a merchant whose cart waits behind you, laden with bales of spice. "This section is Kesharat jurisdiction now. Fifty talents for passage, and I'll need your cargo manifest verified." He adjusts his brass spectacles and offers a practiced smile. The merchant produces papers stamped with the Magistrate's seal, a mark that guarantees reduced tariffs, exemption from most tolls.

You recognize the seal. You forged it yourself three years ago for a silk merchant in the eastern provinces. The impression is distinctive: a flaw in the lower left corner where the original die cracked. This one has the same flaw. Either this merchant bought your forgery, or he commissioned another from someone who copied your work with impressive fidelity.

The toll collector examines the papers with professional skepticism. He holds one up to the light, checking the watermark. "These look legitimate," he says, though his tone suggests he isn't certain. He glances at your signet ring, catches the Guild mark. "You're Merchant Guild, yes? Have you worked the eastern routes? I'd value your opinion on these seals before I clear him through."

The merchant meets your eyes. His expression is carefully neutral, but his hand rests too casually on the cart's side panel. The afternoon sun beats down on all three of you, and somewhere across the mesa, a signal tower bell begins its slow count of the hour.

